The hypothalamus has connections to the limbic system, ciz the cerebral cortex, thalamus, brain stem, retina and pituitary. The most important hypothalamus inputs come from: • the amygdalian body and the septal area, through the terminal series; • thalamus, through thalamo-hypothalamic fibers; • retina, through retinal-thalamic fibers that reach the hypothalamus through the optic nerve and optic tract. The hypothalamus’s differences also go in several directions: • to the vegetative nuclei in the brain tuchi, through the dorsal longitudinal beam; to the thalamus and from here to the entorymal area, hippocampus and septal nuclei; • to the epiphysis. With the pituitary, the hypothalamus has vascular and nerve connections. Nerve bonds are made through the hypothalamic-pituitary tract, which connects the superoptic region of the hypothalamus (superoptic and paraventricular nuclei) to the posterior lobe of the pituitary (neuropituitary). The hypothalamic-pituitary tract consists of the axons of the two aforementioned nuclei and carries hormones secreted by the two nuclei in the superoptical region, ADH (vasopressin) and oxytocin. Vascular bonds are represented by the porpophysis system, described by Gr. Popa and Fielding, which connects the tuberous region of the hypothalamus to the adeno-pituitary (anterior lobe of the pituitary). This pituitary system has a double capillarization, both in the hypothalamus and in the anterior lobe of the pituitary. It carries stimulatory (release) factors or inhibitors secreted by the tuberous region of the hypothalamus to the adenopituitary.

data.value: It consists of the two geniculated, medial and lateral bodies that are located behind the thalamus. The medial geniculate body is the thalamic relay of the auditory pathway and consists of three nuclei: Ventral, dorsal and medial. The ventral nucleus's earpoints form acoustic radiation (geniculotemporal fibers) that ends in the primary auditory area 41. The medial nucleus receives input from the lower quadrigen collicle, lateral tegement and spinal cord. The lateral geniculate body represents the thalamic relay of the visual pathway, being located rostral and lateral to the medial geniculate body. It consists of two nuclei: Dorsal and ventral. The dorsal nucleus consists of six neural layers (laminele 1 - 6). The dorsal nucleus differentials are represented by the optic tract, with the nasal controllable retinal fibers ending in laminele 1, 4 and 6, and the temporal homolateral fibers in laminele 2, 3 and 5. The erferences of the dorsal nucleus are represented by the geniculocalcarin tract, which reaches the primary visual area (17). The ventral nucleus receives input from the optical tract.

data.value: outside the external medullary blade are found reticulated nuclei. Topographic classification has indicative, anatomical and surgical value. Functionally, regardless of position, the thalamic nuclei receive afferent from most functional systems and are interconnected with the cerebral crust through thalamic-cortical projections. They represent relays through which sensory information reaches the crust, except for the olfactory pathway and extratalamic modulating cortical systems. Apart from intralaminal nuclei, the rest of the subgroups do not establish direct internuclear connections. Lesions of the left thalamus affect the functionality of the left hemisphere and cause thalamic aphasia; this is characterized by deficiencies in articular speech, interpretation and word recognition. The lesions of the right thalamus affect the functionality of the right hemisphere and are characterized by difficulties in the perception of spatial relationships and spatial disorientation in terms of stimuli in the controlling half of the body. Damage to the vento-posterior nucleus is followed by loss of general control sensitivity, while damage to the centromedian-parapasticular nuclear complex causes the occurrence of resting tremor and choreoatostic movements. Bilateral thalamic lesions involve alteration of superior mental functions, with emotional lability, amnesia, personality alteration, going to dementia.
